WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.440
Okay, so in the last few modules, you got
the lay of the land.

2
00:00:04.780 --> 00:00:09.820
You know who we are, you know who our sellers
are, and you know what we actually offer

3
00:00:09.820 --> 00:00:10.200
them.

4
00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:13.440
Now let's talk about how deals move through
our system.

5
00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:18.940
Like, from the very first time a lead pops
into our CRM all the way through to a signed

6
00:00:18.940 --> 00:00:23.680
contract. Because there is a system, and you
need to know it cold.

7
00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:27.400
This is the BMH Sales Pipeline.

8
00:00:27.900 --> 00:00:34.340
It has six stages. Every single lead in our
CRM lives in one of these stages at all

9
00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:39.720
times. Your entire job boils down to moving
them forward through these stages, or

10
00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:41.840
disqualifying them and moving on.

11
00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:44.480
Nothing just sits there collecting dust.

12
00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:47.440
If a lead isn't moving, something's wrong.

13
00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:50.440
So let me take you through each one.

14
00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:53.660
Stage one is lead capture.

15
00:00:54.300 --> 00:00:58.560
This is ground zero. A lead enters our
system from somewhere.

16
00:00:58.949 --> 00:01:00.330
Maybe it came from marketing.

17
00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:02.620
Maybe a cold caller got them on the phone.

18
00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:06.520
Maybe they called us. Maybe they texted back
to a campaign.

19
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:08.460
Maybe someone referred them.

20
00:01:08.460 --> 00:01:11.300
At this point, all we really have is the
basics.

21
00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:17.360
A name, a phone number, a property address,
and whatever scraps of info the source

22
00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:21.760
captured. Nobody has had a real conversation
with this person yet.

23
00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:27.160
They're just a name sitting in the CRM
waiting for somebody to reach out.

24
00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:29.120
And that somebody is you.

25
00:01:29.740 --> 00:01:31.020
Your job here is simple.

26
00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:33.520
Make first contact. Call them.

27
00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:35.780
Text them. Email them.

28
00:01:36.100 --> 00:01:38.340
Whatever it takes to start a conversation.

29
00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:44.500
If you can't reach them, they stay in stage
one with a follow-up task assigned.

30
00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:50.480
You don't move them forward until you've
actually had a live conversation with the

31
00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:52.120
seller. That's the exit.

32
00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:56.020
A real, live, two-way conversation.

33
00:01:57.160 --> 00:01:59.660
Stage two is qualification.

34
00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:02.020
So you've made contact.

35
00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:07.140
Cool. Now you need to figure out if this is
someone we can actually help.

36
00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:10.920
This is where you ask the initial qualifying
questions.

37
00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:13.100
Is this person the decision maker?

38
00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:15.160
Do they actually want to sell?

39
00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:16.660
Or were they just curious?

40
00:02:16.660 --> 00:02:19.000
Is the property in one of our markets?

41
00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:22.240
Is there enough equity for a deal to even
make sense?

42
00:02:22.680 --> 00:02:26.940
Are there any obvious red flags that would
kill this before it starts?

43
00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:31.360
Your job at this stage is to run through
that qualification checklist.

44
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:38.480
Confirm the basics. Ownership, property
type, location, general motivation, rough

45
00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:43.760
timeline. You move them out of stage two once
the seller passes initial qualification.

46
00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:49.560
They're the owner, the property fits what we
buy, and there's at least some motivation

47
00:02:49.560 --> 00:02:50.160
there.

48
00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:53.180
Stage three is discovery.

49
00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:57.240
And honestly, this is where the real magic
happens.

50
00:02:57.780 --> 00:02:59.280
You've confirmed the basics.

51
00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:01.620
Great. Now you dig deeper.

52
00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:04.520
What's actually going on in this person's
life?

53
00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:06.420
What's driving them to sell?

54
00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:08.960
What happens if they don't sell?

55
00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:11.000
What's their real timeline?

56
00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:13.680
Not the polite answer, but the honest one.

57
00:03:14.100 --> 00:03:15.660
What have they already tried?

58
00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:17.960
This is the heart of what you do.

59
00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:23.220
Discovery is where you build trust, where
you uncover the real motivation hiding

60
00:03:23.220 --> 00:03:28.260
underneath the surface level answers, and
where you gather all the detailed information

61
00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:32.060
our acquisition team is going to need to put
together an offer.

62
00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:36.460
Your job here is to have a deep, genuine
conversation.

63
00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:39.000
Understand their situation fully.

64
00:03:39.420 --> 00:03:42.140
Fill in every detail in the CRM.

65
00:03:42.900 --> 00:03:48.600
Condition, motivation, timeline,
expectations, financial

66
00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:51.520
situation, who's involved in the decision.

67
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.480
You're done with stage three when you can
clearly explain to someone else why this

68
00:03:56.480 --> 00:04:02.120
person wants to sell, what their timeline
looks like, and what they'd need to see to

69
00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:02.900
move forward.

70
00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:06.580
Stage four is handoff.

71
00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:08.340
The seller is qualified.

72
00:04:08.340 --> 00:04:11.140
They're motivated. You've done your part.

73
00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:17.060
Now it's time to pass this lead over to the
acquisition team so they can evaluate the

74
00:04:17.060 --> 00:04:18.800
property and present an offer.

75
00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:21.480
And I want to be really clear about this.

76
00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:24.160
The handoff is a critical moment.

77
00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:26.900
A sloppy handoff kills deals.

78
00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:29.880
I've seen it happen more times than I can
count.

79
00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:36.560
You need to package everything you've learned,
the seller's story, what's motivating

80
00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:42.660
them, what they're expecting, all the
property details, and pass it cleanly to the

81
00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:43.740
acquisition manager.

82
00:04:43.740 --> 00:04:45.800
Complete the handoff checklist.

83
00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:51.840
Brief the acquisition manager on the seller's
situation, their hot buttons, what to be

84
00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:56.760
careful about. Then either warm transfer the
seller while they're still on the phone

85
00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:00.800
with you or set a specific appointment for
the acquisition's call.

86
00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:05.600
You're done with stage four when the
acquisition team has accepted the lead and has

87
00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:07.920
everything they need to take it from here.

88
00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:11.080
Stage five is offer review.

89
00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:13.680
The acquisition team presents the offer.

90
00:05:14.060 --> 00:05:15.420
The seller reviews it.

91
00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:20.640
There might be some negotiation, counter
offers, questions back and forth.

92
00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:25.400
This stage is primarily run by the
acquisition team, but you might get pulled in.

93
00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:30.300
If the acquisition manager needs you to call
the seller or provide additional context

94
00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:33.940
about something that came up in your
conversations, you jump in and help.

95
00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:36.860
Stage six is contract.

96
00:05:37.340 --> 00:05:39.040
The seller accepts the offer.

97
00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:43.920
Contract gets signed. The deal moves to the
transaction team for closing.

98
00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:48.640
At this point, your work on this particular
lead is basically done.

99
00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:53.920
You might send a congratulatory text or help
tie up a loose end, but the transaction

100
00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:55.360
team handles the rest.

101
00:05:55.755 --> 00:06:00.855
And the relationship you built through all
those earlier stages, that's what made it all

102
00:06:00.855 --> 00:06:01.284
possible.

103
00:06:02.210 --> 00:06:06.070
So let me be really clear about where you
live in all of this.

104
00:06:06.650 --> 00:06:08.930
You own stages one through four.

105
00:06:09.570 --> 00:06:13.390
That's your world. Stage one, you make first
contact.

106
00:06:13.830 --> 00:06:15.950
Stage two, you qualify.

107
00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:18.630
Stage three, you discover.

108
00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:22.010
Stage four, you hand off.

109
00:06:22.010 --> 00:06:27.450
Stages five and six are handled by the
acquisition and transaction teams.

110
00:06:27.910 --> 00:06:33.470
You support when they ask, but your primary
focus is getting leads from stage one all

111
00:06:33.470 --> 00:06:38.170
the way to stage four, as many as possible
and as thoroughly as possible.

112
00:06:38.910 --> 00:06:40.570
And that's the pipeline.

113
00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:43.870
Six stages and you own the first four.

114
00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:49.990
But here's the thing. Inside every one of
these stages, there's a conversation

115
00:06:49.990 --> 00:06:55.410
happening. And every conversation you have
follows a five-step framework.

116
00:06:55.970 --> 00:06:57.590
That's what we'll break down next.

117
00:06:57.817 --> 00:06:58.722
I'll see you there.
